import java.util.*;

public class Solution {
    public static String[] solve(String s) {
        List<String> segments = new ArrayList<>();
        Set<String> seen = new HashSet<>();
        int n = s.length();
        int i = 0;
        while (i < n) {
            int j = i;
            StringBuilder candidate = new StringBuilder();
            boolean found = false;
            while (j < n) {
                candidate.append(s.charAt(j));
                String seg = candidate.toString();
                if (!seen.contains(seg)) {
                    segments.add(seg);
                    seen.add(seg);
                    found = true;
                    break;
                }
                j++;
            }
            if (found) {
                i = j + 1;
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }
        return segments.toArray(new String[0]);
    }
}
```

### Explanation
- **Initialization**: The algorithm initializes an empty list `segments` to store the resulting segments and a set `seen` to keep track of segments that have been processed.
- **Processing Segments**: The outer loop processes each starting position `i` in the string:
  - **Building Segments**: For each starting position `i`, the inner loop builds the segment by appending characters one by one, starting from `i`.
  - **Checking Uniqueness**: For each intermediate segment, the algorithm checks if it exists in the set `seen`. If not, the segment is added to `segments` and `seen`, and the loop breaks to proceed to the next segment starting after the current segment.
  - **Termination**: If no unique segment can be formed from the remaining characters (i.e., all extensions have been seen), the algorithm terminates early.
- **Result Conversion**: The list of segments is converted to an array and returned.

This approach efficiently ensures that all segments added to the result are distinct, processing the string in linear time relative to the input size, with early termination when no further unique segments can be formed.
